Example 1.1
User
What is transfer learning?
AI Response
Transfer learning reuses a model trained on one task as a starting point for another related task, reducing
training time and data requirements significantly.
Example 1.2
User
What is deep learning?
AI Response
Deep learning is a subset of machine learning that uses multi-layered neural networks to learn
representations of data. It excels at tasks like image recognition, NLP, and speech synthesis.
Example 1.3
User
What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response
A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.
Example 1.4
User
What is attention mechanism?
AI Response
Attention allows a model to focus on relevant input parts during output generation. Self-attention in
transformers computes weighted relationships between all token pairs.
Example 1.5
User
What is regularization?
AI Response
Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.
Example 1.6
User
What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response
Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.
Example 1.7
User
What is a loss function?
AI ResponseA loss function quantifies the difference between a model's predictions and the actual targets. Examples
include Mean Squared Error for regression and Cross-Entropy Loss for classification.
Example 1.8
User
What is a transformer model?
AI Response
A transformer is a deep learning architecture using self-attention mechanisms that process all tokens in
parallel, enabling efficient NLP. GPT and BERT are transformer-based models.
Example 1.9
User
What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response
Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.
Example 1.10
User
What is mean squared error?
AI Response
MSE is (1/n) * sum of (predicted - actual)^2. It penalizes large errors heavily and is a standard loss function
for regression tasks, sensitive to outliers.Section 2: Instruction Following
